spec: as3376
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(asyncio)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 672 (as3376): __trunc__, __round__, __index__ dict-presence (math.trunc(x), round(x), operator.index(x)) for asyncio types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: asyncio.Task, asyncio.Future, asyncio.Event, asyncio.Lock, asyncio.Semaphore, asyncio.BoundedSemaphore, asyncio.Condition, asyncio.Queue, asyncio.PriorityQueue, asyncio.LifoQueue."
    - "Key finding (__trunc__): all 10 asyncio classes return false for __trunc__. math.trunc() delegates to __trunc__ when defined; otherwise falls back to __int__. __trunc__ belongs to the numbers.Real protocol. asyncio types implement no numeric data model of any kind — confirmed false across waves 658–671 for all arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, reflected bitwise, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, and rounding operators. math.trunc(event), math.trunc(task), math.trunc(queue) are not valid Python expressions. asyncio types are coroutine-based concurrency primitives with no numeric magnitude to truncate toward zero."
    - "Key finding (__round__): all 10 asyncio classes return false for __round__. The built-in round() delegates to __round__ when defined. __round__ is part of the numbers.Real protocol. asyncio types define no numeric protocol — there is no real-valued magnitude associated with any asyncio concurrency primitive. round(event, n), round(task, n), round(queue, n) are not meaningful Python expressions. asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore encapsulate a permit counter fully behind acquire()/release() coroutines; the counter is not exposed for numeric rounding. asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue are item stores whose qsize() returns an integer, but qsize() is a method — not the object's numeric value — and __round__ is not defined on any Queue subclass."
    - "Key finding (__index__): all 10 asyncio classes return false for __index__. operator.index() requires __index__, which signals that an object can be used as a lossless integer index (e.g., in slice notation or bin()/hex()/oct()). __index__ is defined only on types that are exact integer representations (int subclasses, bool, numpy integers, etc.). asyncio types are coroutine-based concurrency primitives — none of them represent an exact integer value. asyncio.Event/Lock/Condition are boolean-state guards; even though Event.is_set() returns bool and bool.__index__ is true, asyncio.Event itself does not define __index__. asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore encapsulate a counter but the counter is not losslessly extractable as an int via __index__. asyncio.Task/Future are pending coroutine result handles; __index__ is not defined. asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue are item stores; qsize() is a method, not __index__."
    - "Continues the all-false run from wave 656 (__call__/__len__/__getitem__) through wave 672 (__trunc__/__round__/__index__) — seventeen consecutive waves of 100% false results for asyncio types."
    - "Cross-wave summary for asyncio subjects:"
    - "  Wave 656 (as3136): __call__/__len__/__getitem__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 657 (as3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 658 (as3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 659 (as3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 660 (as3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 661 (as3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 662 (as3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 663 (as3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 664 (as3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 665 (as3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 666 (as3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 667 (as3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 668 (as3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 669 (as3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 670 (as3346): __neg__/__pos__/__abs__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 671 (as3361): __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 672 (as3376): __trunc__/__round__/__index__ — all false for all 10."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __trunc__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__trunc__')
#
# All 10 asyncio classes return false for __trunc__.
# math.trunc() delegates to __trunc__ (numbers.Real protocol) when defined.
# asyncio types implement no numeric data model of any kind.
# asyncio.Event/Lock/Condition: boolean-state synchronization guards with no
#   numeric magnitude to truncate; math.trunc(event) is not a valid expression.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore: permit-counter objects whose internal
#   integer state is fully encapsulated behind acquire()/release() coroutines.
#   The counter is not exposed through __trunc__ or any numeric data model method.
# asyncio.Task/Future: pending coroutine result handles; math.trunc(task) and
#   math.trunc(future) are not valid Python expressions.
# asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue: ordered item stores with no numeric
#   data model; math.trunc(queue) is not defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

